* JwtConfig class - This class is a configuration for create a beans of Encoder and Decoder of Token.

1) Create a bean method for KeyPair - Creates the keys.
    @Bean
    public KeyPair keyPair() throws NoSuchAlgorithmException {
        var keyPairGenerator = KeyPairGenerator.getInstance("RSA");
        keyPairGenerator.initialize(2048);
        return keyPairGenerator.generateKeyPair();
    }

2) Create a bean method for RSAKey and inject the KeyPair - Sets up the key with a unique ID.

    @Bean
    public RSAKey rsaKey(KeyPair keyPair){
        return new RSAKey.Builder((RSAPublicKey) keyPair.getPublic())
                .privateKey(keyPair.getPrivate())
                .keyID(UUID.randomUUID().toString())
                .build();
    }

3) Create a bean method for JwkSource and inject the RSAKey - Provides the key in the JWK format.
    @Bean
    public JWKSource<SecurityContext> jwkSource(RSAKey rsaKey){
        var jwkSet = new JWKSet(rsaKey);
        return (jwkSelector,securityContext) -> jwkSelector.select(jwkSet);
    }

4) Then create a bean method for Decoder and inject the RSAKey pair also - Decodes and verifies JWTs.
    @Bean
    public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder(RSAKey rsaKey) throws JOSEException {
        return NimbusJwtDecoder.withPublicKey(rsaKey.toRSAPublicKey()).build();
    }

5) Lastly create a bean method for Encoder and inject the JwkSource - Encodes JWTs using the key source.
    @Bean
    public JwtEncoder jwtEncoder(JWKSource<SecurityContext> jwkSource){
        return new NimbusJwtEncoder(jwkSource);
    }


* JwtService Class - This class is for creating a validation or a business logic of Jwt Encoding and Decoding. Also add
@Service annotation to automatically add this bean to Spring Application Context

1) Add Encoder and Decoder bean. Auto wired it or just use Constructor Injection (use @AllArgsConstructor for
simplicity)

private final JwtEncoder jwtEncoder;
private final JwtDecoder jwtDecoder;

2) Create a method for generating a token - In generating a token, it needs to inject the Authentication object just to
get the userPrincipal of authenticated user.

    public String generateToken(Authentication authentication){

        var userPrincipal = (UserPrincipal) authentication.getPrincipal();

        var claims = JwtClaimsSet.builder()
                .issuer("https://pea-todo-list-application.onrender.com/")
                .issuedAt(Instant.now())
                .expiresAt(Instant.now().plusSeconds(60 * 30))
                .id(userPrincipal.getId().toString())
                .subject(authentication.getName())
                .claim("roles",getClaim(authentication))
                .build();

        var parameters = JwtEncoderParameters.from(claims);

        return jwtEncoder.encode(parameters).getTokenValue();
    }

3) Create a method for getting the claim - It needs also inject the Authentication object to get all Claims or the roles
 of Authenticated user and call this method in claim() method of generateToken method.

    public String getClaim(Authentication authentication){
        return authentication.getAuthorities().stream().map(GrantedAuthority::getAuthority).collect(Collectors.joining(
                " "));
    }

4) Create a method to extract the username of current authenticated user - This method is for getting the username base
on the token provided and use the method of object jwtDecoder.

    public String extractUsername(String token){
        try{
            var username = jwtDecoder.decode(token);
            return username.getSubject();
        }catch (JwtException e){
            logger.error("Failed to extract username from token: {}",e.getMessage());
            return null;
        }
    }


5) Create a method to validate the token first if it's expire and if it's equal to the issuer of my application. "https://pea-todo-list-application.onrender.com/"

    public boolean isTokenValid(String token) {
           try {
               Jwt decodedJwt = jwtDecoder.decode(token);

               // Check token expiration and issuer
               Instant expiration = decodedJwt.getExpiresAt();
               String issuer = decodedJwt.getIssuer().toString();

               return (expiration.isAfter(Instant.now()) && issuer.equals("https://pea-todo-list-application.onrender.com/"));
           } catch (JwtException e) {
               logger.error("Invalid token: {}", e.getMessage());
               return false;
           }
       }